  Elystria's origin. May chose her as the Reaper of her Reality and told her she must leave her family. We see her ordinary life — her husband (kind, patient), her daughter (who reminded her of sunlight). The crane. The frayed cables the workers dismissed. The girl at the park who kept Elystria talking. The building collapses onto the road. Her husband and daughter, caught in traffic, cannot escape. Elystria understands immediately what happened. She blames May. She blames Death. She blames the law that exists only because of him.
  <div class="lore-note" style="background:#fde0dc; border-left-color:#880e4f;">📌 ELYSTRIA: She is the most emotionally expressive reaper — by nature and by wound. She has total control over the elements, wielding them as weapons. Her scythe becomes a whip. She is the opposite of the stoic reaper ideal in every way — and that is exactly why Death chose her, even if she doesn't know it yet. She doesn't want to be a reaper. She doesn't want to live forever.</div></td></tr>

  <tr class="ely-arc"><td><span class="chapter-link">CH 20</span><span class="official-title">"The Sunflower Without the Sun PT2"</span></td>
  <td><span class="badge-low">Low</span></td><td></td><td>Death Faction</td><td><span class="badge-notstarted">NOT STARTED</span></td>
  <td><span class="arc-tag tag-ely">ELYSTRIA</span><span class="arc-tag tag-death">DEATH</span>
  Elystria in the immediate aftermath. She blames Death more than anyone — it was his law that caused this, the law that says a reaper must stay away from their family. She cannot reach him to confront him. She can only grieve. She learns that what happened was not coincidental — it was a consequence of being chosen. This knowledge transforms her grief into rage. A rage she carries quietly for chapters because she is too kind to let it make her cruel. Yet.
  <div class="lore-note gold">📌 DEATH ARC: His law killed Elystria's family. He knows. He has known since the moment she was chosen. He lets things play out. He will not acknowledge it unless forced — not because he doesn't care, but because his emotional architecture doesn't have a mechanism for guilt. His arc is learning to build one.</div></td></tr>

  <tr class="ely-arc"><td><span class="chapter-link">CH 21</span><span class="official-title">"The Sunflower Without the Sun PT3"</span></td>
